ary derived from oral ectoderm","Middle portion of the pituitary containing blood vessels","Connective tissue capsule surrounding the pituitary","Posterior portion of the pituitary derived from neural tissue"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior portion of the pituitary\u003C/strong\u003E (adenohypophysis) develops from Rathke\u0027s pouch, an outgrowth of oral ectoderm. It produces several important hormones including growth hormone, prolactin, thyroid stimulating hormone, adrenocorticotropic hormone, and gonadotropins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior portion\u003C/strong\u003E (neurohypophysis) develops from neural tissue and produces oxytocin and vasopressin. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emiddle portion containing blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the pars intermedia, which is vestigial in humans. The \u003Cstrong\u003Econnective tissue capsule\u003C/strong\u003E is not a functional component of the pituitary. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior portion\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the infundibular stalk, which connects the hypothalamus to the posterior pituitary but is not part of the adenohypophysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The adenohypophysis is the anterior portion of the pituitary gland that develops from Rathke\u0027s pouch.","The adenohypophysis produces and secretes multiple hormones including growth hormone and prolactin, amongst others"],"references":["Hormone supply to the pituitary gland: A comprehensive investigation of female\u2011related tumors (Review). Int J Mol Med. 2022 Oct;50(4):122. doi: 10.3892/ijmm.2022.5178. Epub 2022 Aug 10. PMID: 35946461; PMCID: PMC9387558","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook o